article.description:
Shareef Abdur-Rahim had 11 of his 26 points in
the fourth quarter Monday night, helping the Atlanta Hawks hold off
the struggling Los Angeles Clippers 95-86.
article.headline: Abdur-Rahim scores 11 of  26 in fourth quarter
article.linkText: Abdur-Rahim scores 26 as Hawks hold off Clippers
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- With the offense running through Shareef Abdur-Rahim, the Atlanta Hawks were in good hands.
 
Abdur-Rahim
Abdur-Rahim had 11 of his 26 points in the fourth quarter Monday night, helping the Atlanta Hawks hold off the struggling Los Angeles Clippers 95-86. Dion Glover added 14 points as the Hawks put all their starters in double figures for the first time in 22 games. Abdur-Rahim grabbed 15 rebounds, and Theo Ratliff had three blocks. "I was just trying to make plays," Abdur-Rahim said. "I don't have to score the ball every time. I was just trying to get the defense to come to me, and then if they came, get the ball to the other guys." He spent most of the game battling in the lane against rookies Melvin Ely and Chris Wilcox. "We were telling him before the game, they've got a lot of rookies, you've got to show them who's boss," Atlanta point guard Jason Terry said. The Hawks have won three of their last four. The Clippers are going the other way, losing nine of 10. Corey Maggette scored 14 of their 18 points in the first quarter, but cooled off after spraining an ankle and finished with 19. Ely added 13 off the bench, one short of his career high. "We just kind of got away from some stuff," Maggette said. "I'm very disappointed. We were capable of winning that game." Atlanta led by 11 after three quarters, but Los Angeles scored the first four points of the period to cut it to seven. Going to Abdur-Rahim nearly every time downcourt, the Hawks eventually pushed the lead to 13. During the run, he tipped in his own miss and added another layup, and Ira Newble scored after a nice pass from Glenn Robinson on the fastbreak. "We did a lot of good things," Atlanta coach Terry Stotts said. "I thought we moved the ball, played unselfishly." But the Clippers weren't done. They closed within four behind Ely, who's been playing more since coach Dennis Johnson took over when Alvin Gentry was fired. He had his way inside, even with Ratliff guarding him, and got his final points on a thunderous dunk off a missed 3-pointer from Andre Miller with 1:49 left. "Coach has a lot of confidence in me in the fourth quarter," Ely said. Abdur-Rahim was too much, though. With the lead at four, he made three free throws and hit a hook from the lane to boost the margin back to nine, then helped set up a 3-pointer by Terry to give Atlanta a 91-81 lead with 3:04 left. "Those young guys they have are very talented, but they're still learning," Abdur-Rahim said. "I've got a little experience on them." Maggette scored from in close on the next possession, but the Clippers missed five of their last six shots. "I felt like we were in control most of the game," Abdur-Rahim said. "We did have a lapse or two there in the fourth quarter, but we got it straightened out." Ratliff and Robinson had 13 apiece for the Hawks, and Terry scored 12. Game notes
After allowing more than 100 points five straight games, the Clippers haven't given up that many in four in a row. ... Los Angeles G Quentin Richardson missed the game with strained left knee. ... The Hawks have won eight straight against the Clippers in Atlanta.
